Let $I$ be the incenter of triangle $ABC,$ and let $E$ and $F$ be the points where the incircle is tangent to $BC$ and $AC,$ respectively.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, I;

B = (0,0);
C = (20,0);
D = (B + C)/2;
I = extension(B, B + dir(110), C, C + dir(70));
A = extension(I, I + dir(110), D, D + dir(110));
E = foot(I,B,C);
F = foot(I,A,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);
draw(incircle(A,B,C));

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, S);
label("$F$", F, NE);
label("$I$", I, NW);
[/asy]

Since the incircle evenly trisects median $AD,$ $AI = ID = \frac{1}{2} AD.$  Also, $BE = BF$ and $CE = CF.$

Since $BE = BF$ and $CE = CF,$ triangles $IBE$ and $ICF$ are congruent, so $\angle IBE = \angle ICF.$  Also, $\angle IBE + \angle IBC = 90^\circ,$ so $\angle ICF + \angle IBC = 90^\circ.$  Hence, $\angle BIC = 180^\circ - (\angle ICF + \angle IBC) = 90^\circ,$ so triangle $BIC$ is a right triangle.

Let $r$ be the inradius of triangle $ABC.$  Then the area of triangle $ABC$ is $[ABC] = rs,$ where $s$ is the semiperimeter of triangle $ABC.$  Also, $[BIC] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot BC \cdot r = 10r.$

Since $AI = ID,$
\[[ABI] = [CID] = \frac{1}{2} [ABC].\]Then
\[[BIC] = [ABC] - [ABI] - [CID] = \frac{1}{2} [ABC] = \frac{1}{2} rs.\]Hence, $10r = \frac{1}{2} rs,$ so $s = 20.$

Let $a = BC = 20,$ $b = AC,$ and $c = AB.$  Then $s = \frac{a + b + c}{2} = 20,$ so $b + c = 40.$  Also, $b - c = 2 \cdot BE = 2r.$

Solving, we find $b = 20 + r$ and $c = 20 - r.$  Then
\[[ABC] = rs = r \cdot \frac{a + b + c}{2} = r \cdot 20 = 20r.\]Also,
\[[ABC] = \sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)} = \sqrt{20 \cdot 0 \cdot (20 - b)(20 - c)} = \sqrt{20r^2}.\]Hence, $20r = \sqrt{20r^2},$ so $r = \sqrt{5}.$

Therefore, $[ABC] = 20r = 20 \sqrt{5},$ and $m + n = 20 + 5 = \boxed{25}.$

